# Glossary

Short definitions for every term that appears across these docs. Most
entries link back to the chapter where they're explained in depth.

### Backend
This project's name for a swappable DDS implementation. See
[Backends](#docs/backends).

### BestEffort
A [Reliability](#docs/qos) QoS value: send once, no retransmission, no
acknowledgement. Fast and lossy.

### CDR
**Common Data Representation** — the OMG-standardized wire format for
DDS payloads. See [Serialization](#docs/cdr).

### DataReader / DataWriter
The objects that actually send and receive samples on a topic. See
[The DDS objects](#docs/dds-objects).

### DCPSParticipant, DCPSPublication, DCPSSubscription, DCPSTopic, DCPSParticipantMessage
The five **builtin topics** every DomainParticipant maintains for
discovery and liveliness. See [The 5 builtin topics in
detail](#docs/builtin-topics).

### Deadline
QoS policy specifying max time between samples on a topic instance.

### Discovery
The process of participants finding each other and exchanging endpoint
info without configuration. See [Discovery](#docs/discovery).

### Domain
A numbered logical bus. Two participants on the same domain can match
their writers and readers; different domains are invisible to each
other.

### DomainParticipant
The root DDS object representing a process's membership in a domain.

### Durability
A [QoS](#docs/qos) policy: whether late joiners receive samples written
before they joined.

### EntityId
The last 4 bytes of a [GUID](#docs/endpoints) identifying a specific
writer / reader within a participant.

### GuidPrefix
The first 12 bytes of a [GUID](#docs/endpoints), shared by all entities
on the same DomainParticipant.

### GUID
**Globally Unique Identifier** — 16 bytes that uniquely name any
DDS endpoint on the bus. See [Endpoints, GUIDs,
instances](#docs/endpoints).

### HDDS
A pure-Rust DDS implementation by hdds-team. See
[Backends](#docs/backends).

### History
Local-only QoS bounding how many samples each writer/reader keeps in
its cache.

### Instance
A sub-stream within a WITH_KEY topic, distinguished by the key value.
See [Endpoints, GUIDs, instances](#docs/endpoints).

### Key
A field (or group of fields) on a WITH_KEY topic's payload type used to
identify which instance a sample belongs to.

### Liveliness
QoS policy + status event combo for "is the writer still alive?". See
[QoS](#docs/qos).

### Locator
A `(transport, port, address)` triple advertised in SPDP describing how
to reach a participant unicast.

### Matching
The middleware step where a local writer and a remote reader (or
vice-versa) confirm topic + QoS compatibility and start exchanging data.

### Multicast
UDP one-to-many transport, used by SPDP for the bootstrap announcements.

### NO_KEY
A topic kind where the whole topic is a single sample stream (no
instance partitioning).

### OMG
**Object Management Group** — the standards body publishing the DDS,
RTPS, CDR, XTypes, and DDS-Security specifications.

### Ownership
QoS policy: whether one writer or many can write to the same instance.

### Participant
Short for [DomainParticipant](#docs/dds-objects).

### PL_CDR
**Parameter-List CDR** — a self-describing variant of CDR used by
discovery payloads. Each field carries its own ID and length, so
readers can skip unknown fields.

### Publisher / Subscriber
DDS objects that own DataWriters / DataReaders and hold default QoS.
Mostly invisible in practice.

### QoS
**Quality of Service** — the typed contract attached to writers and
readers. See [QoS — the matching contract](#docs/qos).

### Reliability
[QoS](#docs/qos) policy: BestEffort or Reliable.

### RepresentationIdentifier
The 2-byte header at the start of every CDR payload, telling decoders
which CDR variant follows. See [Serialization](#docs/cdr).

### rmw
ROS Middleware abstraction layer — ROS 2's equivalent of this project's
`DdsBackend` trait. See [ROS 2 on top of DDS](#docs/ros2).

### ROS 2
Robot Operating System 2 — the largest user-visible DDS deployment. See
[ROS 2 on top of DDS](#docs/ros2).

### RTPS
**Real-Time Publish-Subscribe Protocol** — the OMG-standardized wire
protocol DDS implementations speak. Independent from the DDS API.

### RustDDS
A pure-Rust DDS implementation by Atostek. This app's default backend.

### Sample
One value sent through a writer to a reader on a topic.

### SEDP
**Simple Endpoint Discovery Protocol** — the SPDP follow-up where
participants exchange writer/reader info over the four
`DCPSPublication`/`DCPSSubscription`/`DCPSTopic` builtin topics. See
[Discovery](#docs/discovery).

### SPDP
**Simple Participant Discovery Protocol** — the multicast-based
bootstrap where participants announce their existence. See
[Discovery](#docs/discovery).

### TopicKind
WITH_KEY or NO_KEY. Part of a topic's identity.

### TransientLocal
A Durability QoS value: keep written samples in the writer's local
cache so late joiners can replay them.

### Vendor / VendorId
A 2-byte identifier in SPDP saying which DDS implementation is talking.
Pretty-printed in the Participants sidebar.

### Volatile
The default Durability — late joiners get nothing past.

### WITH_KEY
A topic kind where samples are grouped by a key field into independent
instances.

### XCDR2
The newer CDR variant (added by the XTypes 1.x spec) supporting
optional fields, mutable types, and forward/backward compatibility.

### XTypes
The OMG spec for dynamic type discovery, type evolution, and type
compatibility checking over DDS. RustDDS has partial support; HDDS has
full 1.3 support.
